Red Wine Quality Exploration by Yanrong Mu

Introduction: This report explores a dataset containing 1,599 red wines with 11 variables on the chemical properties of the wine and the quality of each wine, providing a rating between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent).

Our dataset consists of 12 variables (variable X can be considered as ID), with almost 1,599 observations. The structure of dataset and summary of each variable are shown above.

##   3   4   5   6   7   8 
##  10  53 681 638 199  18

I add a new variable quality.level, which has same values with quality but an ordered factor variable, which is easier to do analysis later. From the information of this dataset, we knew that the quality is scored from 0 (worst) to 10 (best). After changing the structure, we noticed from the summary of variable quality.level that there are only scores from 3 to 8, which means no red wine is scored by 0, 1, 2, 9 and 10.

Most of red wines are of quality 5 or 6, with fewer red wines of quality 7. There are almost no red wines of quality 3 or 8, which means most red wines are of middle quality. The distribution of quality can be considered as a normal distribution.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    4.60    7.10    7.90    8.32    9.20   15.90

The shape of fixed acidity is a little bit skewed to the right. Most red wines have fixed acidity between 7.1 g/dm^3 and 8.1 g/dm^3: median 7.9 g/dm^3 and mean 8.32 g/dm^3.

Most red wines have volatile acidity around 0.4 g/dm^3 or 0.6 g/dm^3: median 0.52 g/dm^3 and mean 0.5278 g/dm^3. There are only few red wines of high volatile acidity, maybe because too high of levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste.

According to the documentation of this dataset, sulphates can contribute to sulfur dioxide gas (S02) levels. So I guess there will be some relationshape between variable sulphates and variable total.sulfur.dioxide. By comparing their own plots, its not easy to see the relationship, so Ill do bivariate plot later to check their relationship.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 1,599 red wines in the dataset with 12 features (fixed acidity, vlatile acidity, citric acid, residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide, density, PH, sulphates, alcohol, quality).

I changed variable quality to ordered factor variabe with levels 0(worst) - 10(best). Other variables are all numbers.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main features in the dataset are acidity, and quality. Id like to determine which features are best for predicting the quality of a red wine. Only based on plots of variables, its hard to say which feature is more affactable on quality of red wine. I suspect some combination of the other variables can be used to build a predictive model to test the qualify of red wine.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

Acidity, sugar, chlorides, density, pH, sulphates and alcohol likely contribute to the quality of a red wine. I think acidity, sugar and alcohol probably contribute most to the quality after researching information on red wine. Also, I think there should be some relationship between sulphates and sulfur dioxide level.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I create a new variable quality.level, which is changing quality to an ordered factor variable, which makes later analysis easier to follow.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

I log-transformed the right skewed free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide distribution. The tranformed distribution for sulfur dioxide appears normal.

Bivariate Plots Section

From scatterplot matrices, residual.sugur, free.sulfur.dioxide and pH do not seem to have strong correlations with quality, while volatile.acidity and alcohol have a relatively strong correlations with quality. I also want to look closer at scatter plots involving quality and some other variables like citric.acid and sulphates.

Other interesting observation between features:

  • Theres quite strong correlations between fixed.acidity, volatile.acidity and citric.acid.
  • Theres some relationship between fixed.acidity and density.
  • Theres one thing against what I guessed before, which is that sulphates has very low correlations with sulfur.dioxide, but it has moderate correlation with chlorides, surprisingly.

Next, Ill look closer to those interesting observations between features based on the correlation matrices.

As fixed acidity increases, the overall trend of citric acidity is increasing, but we still see variance in citric acidity. There can be some linear relationship between fixed acidity and citric acidity.

Adding jitter, transparency, and changing the plot limits lets us see the slight correlation between table and price, which is surprised me. I thought larger amount of sulphates would corresponding to higher level sulfur dioxide.

Even after adding jitter, transparency, and changing the plot limits, we still cannot see the relationship between chlorides and sulphates, which conflict with their correlation value.

We can see that theres no strong correlation between variables volatile.acidity and alcohol, so we could use both of these two variables to predict the quality.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?

Quality correlates strongly with acidity and alcohol level.

As quality increases, the level of volatile acidity deceases, while level of citric acidity increases.

Overall, higher quality corresponding to higher level of alcohol, expect quality 5, which having a lowest average alcohol level.

Also, we can see that as quality becomes higher, amount of sulphates red wine contains will be slightly increasing.

Surprisingly, amount of sugar doesnt have much affect to the quality.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?

As fixed acidity increases, the overall trend of citric acidity is increasing. Although the relationship between fixed acidity and citric acidity doesnt look like a perfect linear relationship, based on the R^2 value, fixed.acidity still explains about 45 percent of the variance found in citric.acid.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The quality of a red wine is negatively and strongly correlated with amount of volatile acidity. The variables alcohol and citric.acid positively correlate with the quality but less strongly than volatile acidity.
